\begin{definition*}[Co-design problem with implementation]
    {}
    A \maindef{co-design problem with implementation} (CDPI) is a tuple~$\tup{\funsp,\ressp, \tup{\cdpiN,\cdpiE}}$, where~\funsp and~\ressp are two \SY{posets}, and~$\tup{\cdpiN,\cdpiE}$ is a multigraph of DPIs.
    Each node~$\adp\setin\cdpiN$ is a DPI~$\adp=\tup{\funsp_{\adp},\ressp_{\adp},\impsp_{\adp},\prov_{\adp},\req_{\adp}}.
    $
    An edge~$\cdpie\setin\cdpiE$ is a tuple $\cdpie=\tup{\tup{\adpan{1},\cdpiresindA}, \tup{\adpan{2},\cdpifunindB}}$, where~$\adpan{1},\adpan{2}\setin\cdpiN$ are two nodes and~$\cdpiresindA$ and~$\cdpifunindB$ are the indices of the components of the functionality and resources to be connected, and it holds that~$\pi_{\cdpiresindA}\ressp_{\adpan{1}}=\pi_{\cdpifunindB}\funsp_{\adpan{2}}$~(\cref{fig:mcdps}).

\end{definition*}
